[Student "W"]
{The bidding has been as shown. The contract is 3NT 

Lead the \H4.

This is a close call. The top of your \S honor sequence is very tempting, but even when you find partner with the \SK you can still only establish three \S winners to go with your \CA. Unfortunately, that's not enough to defeat the contract.

Leading a \H from your 5-card suit is riskier, but it has the potential of setting up an additional winner. In this hand, as you see, the \H lead gets you 4 \H winners to go with your \CA. }
[Play "W"]H4

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:A93.QJ743.K.K874 84.982.AT53.AJ62 KJ75.AK65.8742.5 QT62.T.QJ96.QT93"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 1S pass 2C pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "59a17bd3f27882fd10e040d595eb4ba4cfb38cf4ed7c64e19e751e50473ab13f"]
[Category "Defense"]
[Difficulty "beginner"]
[SkillPath "defense/opening_leads"]
[Student "W"]
{The bidding has been as shown. The contract is 4\H 

Underleading an Ace against a suit contract is the absolute worst opening lead in Bridge. A careful look at this hand shows just how bad it can turn out.

And leading from a doubleton in a suit the opponents have bid is almost as bad.

So by process of elimination you lead a trump, probably the \H9.

And when East plays \Cs, (preparing to ruff in dummy), you will win and play another trump. Even if East guesses the \Ss correctly he will not be able to make the contract. }
[Play "W"]H9

